
---

Stage 2 — System Control, Safety, and Observability

Overview

Stage 2 focuses on evolving the system from a functional local AI assistant into a safe, controllable, and observable remote system operator.

The priorities for this stage are:

reducing risk (privilege separation and restricted access)

enabling controlled system operations (power, services, network)

adding visibility into system health

introducing monitoring and alerting

improving safety of tool execution


This stage shifts the project from:

“useful assistant”

to:

“reliable operational interface for a headless server”


---

Stage 2 Objectives

introduce strict privilege separation

safely enable remote power control

implement Wake-on-LAN for recovery

provide system visibility (temps, services, logs)

add monitoring and alerting

replace unsafe command execution with structured tools

prepare system for future automation and expansion



---

Phase 2.1 — Privilege Separation and Hardening

Goal

Run the bot as a dedicated service account with minimal permissions.

Tasks

create a dedicated system user for the bot

move the systemd service to run under this user

restrict file ownership and access to project directory

define explicit sudo permissions for allowed commands only

remove or restrict broad shell execution (/run)


Notes

This must be completed before adding high-impact features such as reboot, shutdown, or firewall control.

Output

isolated bot runtime environment

reduced risk of accidental or malicious system changes



---

Phase 2.2 — Safe Power Control

Goal

Enable controlled remote reboot and shutdown of the server.

Tasks

add /reboot confirm command

add /shutdown confirm command

ensure commands are:

explicit

confirmation-protected

not triggered via natural language


log all power actions


Notes

Power commands must never be automatically triggered by AI or inferred from user intent.

Output

safe, deliberate remote power control



---

Phase 2.3 — Wake-on-LAN

Goal

Enable remote power-on of the server after shutdown.

Tasks

enable Wake-on-LAN in BIOS/UEFI

enable WoL in the operating system

identify and document:

network interface

MAC address


test wake functionality from another device

define external trigger method (e.g. another machine or mobile app)


Notes

Wake-on-LAN cannot be triggered from the powered-off server itself.

Output

reliable recovery path after shutdown



---

Phase 2.4 — Monitoring Visibility Commands

Goal

Provide real-time system status through the bot.

Commands

/temps → CPU and GPU temperatures

/gpu → GPU usage and status

/ip → network addresses and hostname

/services → status of key services

/journal <service> → recent logs (whitelisted services only)


Notes

These commands should be read-only and safe.

Output

improved remote visibility into system state



---

Phase 2.5 — Monitoring and Alerting

Goal

Automatically detect and report system issues.

Tasks

implement background monitoring checks:

CPU temperature

GPU temperature

disk usage

memory usage

service availability


define alert thresholds

send alerts via Telegram

optionally summarize alerts using the AI model


Notes

Monitoring logic should be deterministic and not rely on AI decision-making.

Output

proactive system health notifications



---

Phase 2.6 — Safer Tool Execution and Automation

Goal

Replace broad command execution with structured and safe tools.

Tasks

define tool categories:

read-only tools

action tools


introduce confirmation requirements for state-changing actions

restrict or remove generic /run command

implement tool whitelist

optionally introduce tool registry for management


Notes

This phase ensures the system remains safe as more capabilities are added.

Output

controlled and auditable tool execution



---

Phase 2.7 — Network and Firewall Control

Goal

Allow safe management of network rules.

Tasks

implement wrapper scripts for firewall operations

add commands:

list blocked IPs

block IP

unblock IP


require confirmation for all actions

log all changes

protect:

local network ranges

VPN (Tailscale) network

trusted access paths



Notes

Firewall control must be explicit and never AI-driven.

Output

safe and auditable network control



---

Phase 2.8 — Backup and Version Control

Goal

Ensure system can be restored and maintained reliably.

Tasks

create private GitHub repository

add:

.gitignore

.env.example

documentation


commit stable codebase

document setup and recovery process


Notes

Sensitive data must not be committed.

Output

reproducible and maintainable project state



---

Recommended Execution Order

1. Privilege separation and hardening


2. Safe power control


3. Wake-on-LAN


4. Monitoring visibility commands


5. Monitoring and alerting


6. Safer tool execution and automation


7. Network and firewall control


8. GitHub backup and documentation




---

Summary

Stage 2 transforms the system into a controlled operational tool by:

reducing risk through isolation and permission control

enabling safe remote management

adding visibility and alerting

preparing for structured automation


The result is a system that is not only functional, but also safe, maintainable, and suitable for real-worlrd usage.
